The channel matrix rows correspond to transmitted symbols, and columns to received symbols. With equally likely inputs, maximum-likelihood decoding chooses the transmitted symbol that maximizes the column entry for the observed output.  

For each column, the largest entry is 0.5 (first column, first row), 0.3 (second column, tie between rows), and 0.5 (third column, second row). The probability of correct decision is the sum over columns of (input probability) × (max entry in that column) = (1/3)(0.5 + 0.3 + 0.5) = 1.3/3 = 13/30, so error probability is 1 − 13/30 = 17/30.  

\boxed{F}
